  chapters:
  - verses:
    - title: Prologue
      content: "There once was a man named Job who lived in the land of Uz. He was
        blameless\u2014a man of complete integrity. He feared God and stayed away
        from evil. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He had seven sons and three daughters. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He owned 7,000 sheep, 3,000 camels, 500 teams of oxen, and 500 female
        donkeys. He also had many servants. He was, in fact, the richest person in
        that entire area.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Job\u2019s sons would take turns preparing feasts in their homes,
        and they would also invite their three sisters to celebrate with them. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When these celebrations ended\u2014sometimes after several days\u2014Job
        would purify his children. He would get up early in the morning and offer
        a burnt offering for each of them. For Job said to himself, \u201CPerhaps
        my children have sinned and have cursed God in their hearts.\u201D This was
        Job\u2019s regular practice.  "
      comments: []
    - title: "Job\u2019s First Test"
      content: "One day the members of the heavenly court[COMMENT[0]] came to present
        themselves before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t, and the Accuser, Satan,[COMMENT[1]]
        came with them. "
      comments:
      - number: '1:6a '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: the sons of God.
      - number: '1:6b '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: 'and the satan; '
        - ft: similarly throughout this chapter.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhere have you come from?\u201D the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        asked Satan.\n\tSatan answered the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t, \u201CI
        have been patrolling the earth, watching everything that\u2019s going on.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> asked Satan, \u201CHave you
        noticed my servant Job? He is the finest man in all the earth. He is blameless\u2014a
        man of complete integrity. He fears God and stays away from evil.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Satan replied to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t, \u201CYes,
        but Job has good reason to fear God. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You have always put a wall of protection around him and his home
        and his property. You have made him prosper in everything he does. Look how
        rich he is! '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But reach out and take away everything he has, and he will surely
        curse you to your face!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAll right, you may test him,\u201D the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        said to Satan. \u201CDo whatever you want with everything he possesses, but
        don\u2019t harm him physically.\u201D So Satan left the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t\u2019s
        presence.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "One day when Job\u2019s sons and daughters were feasting at the oldest
        brother\u2019s house, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "a messenger arrived at Job\u2019s home with this news: \u201CYour
        oxen were plowing, with the donkeys feeding beside them, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "when the Sabeans raided us. They stole all the animals and killed
        all the farmhands. I am the only one who escaped to tell you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "While he was still speaking, another messenger arrived with this
        news: \u201CThe fire of God has fallen from heaven and burned up your sheep
        and all the shepherds. I am the only one who escaped to tell you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "While he was still speaking, a third messenger arrived with this
        news: \u201CThree bands of Chaldean raiders have stolen your camels and killed
        your servants. I am the only one who escaped to tell you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "While he was still speaking, another messenger arrived with this
        news: \u201CYour sons and daughters were feasting in their oldest brother\u2019s
        home. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Suddenly, a powerful wind swept in from the wilderness and hit the
        house on all sides. The house collapsed, and all your children are dead.
        I am the only one who escaped to tell you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Job stood up and tore his robe in grief. Then he shaved his head
        and fell to the ground to worship. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He said,\n\t\u201CI came naked from my mother\u2019s womb,\n\tand
        I will be naked when I leave.\n\tThe <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> gave me
        what I had,\n\tand the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has taken it away.\n\tPraise
        the name of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: In all of this, Job did not sin by blaming God.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: "Job\u2019s Second Test"
      content: "One day the members of the heavenly court[COMMENT[0]] came again
        to present themselves before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t, and the
        Accuser, Satan,[COMMENT[1]] came with them. "
      comments:
      - number: '2:1a '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: the sons of God.
      - number: '2:1b '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: 'and the satan; '
        - ft: similarly throughout this chapter.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhere have you come from?\u201D the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        asked Satan.\n\tSatan answered the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t, \u201CI
        have been patrolling the earth, watching everything that\u2019s going on.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> asked Satan, \u201CHave you
        noticed my servant Job? He is the finest man in all the earth. He is blameless\u2014a
        man of complete integrity. He fears God and stays away from evil. And he
        has maintained his integrity, even though you urged me to harm him without
        cause.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Satan replied to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t, \u201CSkin
        for skin! A man will give up everything he has to save his life. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But reach out and take away his health, and he will surely curse
        you to your face!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAll right, do with him as you please,\u201D the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        said to Satan. \u201CBut spare his life.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Satan left the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t\u2019s presence,
        and he struck Job with terrible boils from head to foot.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Job scraped his skin with a piece of broken pottery as he sat among
        the ashes. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "His wife said to him, \u201CAre you still trying to maintain your
        integrity? Curse God and die.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Job replied, \u201CYou talk like a foolish woman. Should we accept
        only good things from the hand of God and never anything bad?\u201D So in
        all this, Job said nothing wrong.  "
      comments: []
    - title: "Job\u2019s Three Friends Share His Anguish"
      content: "When three of Job\u2019s friends heard of the tragedy he had suffered,
        they got together and traveled from their homes to comfort and console him.
        Their names were Eliphaz the Temanite, Bildad the Shuhite, and Zophar the
        Naamathite. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When they saw Job from a distance, they scarcely recognized him.
        Wailing loudly, they tore their robes and threw dust into the air over their
        heads to show their grief. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: Then they sat on the ground with him for seven days and nights. No
        one said a word to Job, for they saw that his suffering was too great for
        words.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: "Job\u2019s First Speech"
      content: 'At last Job spoke, and he cursed the day of his birth. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He said:  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CLet the day of my birth be erased,\n\tand the night I was conceived.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Let that day be turned to darkness.\n\tLet it be lost even to God
        on high,\n\tand let no light shine on it.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Let the darkness and utter gloom claim that day for its own.\n\tLet
        a black cloud overshadow it,\n\tand let the darkness terrify it.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Let that night be blotted off the calendar,\n\tnever again to be
        counted among the days of the year,\n\tnever again to appear among the months.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Let that night be childless.\n\tLet it have no joy.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Let those who are experts at cursing\u2014\n\twhose cursing could
        rouse Leviathan[COMMENT[0]]\u2014\n\tcurse that day.  "
      comments:
      - number: '3:8 '
        contents:
        - ft: The identification of Leviathan is disputed, ranging from an earthly
            creature to a mythical sea monster in ancient literature.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "Let its morning stars remain dark.\n\tLet it hope for light, but
        in vain;\n\tmay it never see the morning light.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Curse that day for failing to shut my mother\u2019s womb,\n\tfor
        letting me be born to see all this trouble.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhy wasn\u2019t I born dead?\n\tWhy didn\u2019t I die as I
        came from the womb?  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Why was I laid on my mother\u2019s lap?\n\tWhy did she nurse me at
        her breasts?  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Had I died at birth, I would now be at peace.\n\tI would be asleep
        and at rest.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I would rest with the world\u2019s kings and prime ministers,\n\twhose
        great buildings now lie in ruins.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I would rest with princes, rich in gold,\n\twhose palaces were filled
        with silver.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Why wasn\u2019t I buried like a stillborn child,\n\tlike a baby who
        never lives to see the light?  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "For in death the wicked cause no trouble,\n\tand the weary are at
        rest.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Even captives are at ease in death,\n\twith no guards to curse them.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Rich and poor are both there,\n\tand the slave is free from his master.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201COh, why give light to those in misery,\n\tand life to those
        who are bitter?  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They long for death, and it won\u2019t come.\n\tThey search for death
        more eagerly than for hidden treasure.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They\u2019re filled with joy when they finally die,\n\tand rejoice
        when they find the grave.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Why is life given to those with no future,\n\tthose God has surrounded
        with difficulties?  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I cannot eat for sighing;\n\tmy groans pour out like water.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "What I always feared has happened to me.\n\tWhat I dreaded has come
        true.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I have no peace, no quietness.\n\tI have no rest; only trouble comes.\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: "Eliphaz\u2019s First Response to Job"
      content: 'Then Eliphaz the Temanite replied to Job:  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWill you be patient and let me say a word?\n\tFor who could
        keep from speaking out?  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CIn the past you have encouraged many people;\n\tyou have strengthened
        those who were weak.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Your words have supported those who were falling;\n\tyou encouraged
        those with shaky knees.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But now when trouble strikes, you lose heart.\n\tYou are terrified
        when it touches you.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Doesn\u2019t your reverence for God give you confidence?\n\tDoesn\u2019t
        your life of integrity give you hope?  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CStop and think! Do the innocent die?\n\tWhen have the upright
        been destroyed?  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "My experience shows that those who plant trouble\n\tand cultivate
        evil will harvest the same.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "A breath from God destroys them.\n\tThey vanish in a blast of his
        anger.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The lion roars and the wildcat snarls,\n\tbut the teeth of strong
        lions will be broken.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The fierce lion will starve for lack of prey,\n\tand the cubs of
        the lioness will be scattered.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThis truth was given to me in secret,\n\tas though whispered
        in my ear.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "It came to me in a disturbing vision at night,\n\twhen people are
        in a deep sleep.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Fear gripped me,\n\tand my bones trembled.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "A spirit[COMMENT[0]] swept past my face,\n\tand my hair stood on
        end.[COMMENT[1]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '4:15a '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: 'wind; '
        - ft: also in 4:16.
          body: 
      - number: '4:15b '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: its wind sent shivers up my spine.
    - title: 
      content: "The spirit stopped, but I couldn\u2019t see its shape.\n\tThere was
        a form before my eyes.\n\tIn the silence I heard a voice say,  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u2018Can a mortal be innocent before God?\n\tCan anyone be pure
        before the Creator?\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CIf God does not trust his own angels\n\tand has charged his
        messengers with foolishness,  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "how much less will he trust people made of clay!\n\tThey are made
        of dust, crushed as easily as a moth.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They are alive in the morning but dead by evening,\n\tgone forever
        without a trace.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Their tent-cords are pulled and the tent collapses,\n\tand they die
        in ignorance."
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: "Eliphaz\u2019s Response Continues"
      content: "\u201CCry for help, but will anyone answer you?\n\tWhich of the angels[COMMENT[0]]
        will help you?  "
      comments:
      - number: '5:1 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: the holy ones.
    - title: 
      content: "Surely resentment destroys the fool,\n\tand jealousy kills the simple.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I have seen that fools may be successful for the moment,\n\tbut then
        comes sudden disaster.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Their children are abandoned far from help;\n\tthey are crushed in
        court with no one to defend them.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The hungry devour their harvest,\n\teven when it is guarded by brambles.[COMMENT[0]]The
        thirsty pant after their wealth.[COMMENT[1]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '5:5a '
        contents:
        - ft: The meaning of the Hebrew for this phrase is uncertain.
          body: 
      - number: '5:5b '
        contents:
        - ft: 'As in Greek and Syriac versions; Hebrew reads '
          body: A snare snatches their wealth.
    - title: 
      content: "But evil does not spring from the soil,\n\tand trouble does not sprout
        from the earth.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "People are born for trouble\n\tas readily as sparks fly up from a
        fire.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CIf I were you, I would go to God\n\tand present my case to
        him.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He does great things too marvelous to understand.\n\tHe performs
        countless miracles.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He gives rain for the earth\n\tand water for the fields.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He gives prosperity to the poor\n\tand protects those who suffer.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He frustrates the plans of schemers\n\tso the work of their hands
        will not succeed.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He traps the wise in their own cleverness\n\tso their cunning schemes
        are thwarted.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They find it is dark in the daytime,\n\tand they grope at noon as
        if it were night.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He rescues the poor from the cutting words of the strong,\n\tand
        rescues them from the clutches of the powerful.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And so at last the poor have hope,\n\tand the snapping jaws of the
        wicked are shut.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBut consider the joy of those corrected by God!\n\tDo not despise
        the discipline of the Almighty when you sin.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "For though he wounds, he also bandages.\n\tHe strikes, but his hands
        also heal.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "From six disasters he will rescue you;\n\teven in the seventh, he
        will keep you from evil.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He will save you from death in time of famine,\n\tfrom the power
        of the sword in time of war.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "You will be safe from slander\n\tand have no fear when destruction
        comes.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "You will laugh at destruction and famine;\n\twild animals will not
        terrify you.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "You will be at peace with the stones of the field,\n\tand its wild
        animals will be at peace with you.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "You will know that your home is safe.\n\tWhen you survey your possessions,
        nothing will be missing.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "You will have many children;\n\tyour descendants will be as plentiful
        as grass!  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "You will go to the grave at a ripe old age,\n\tlike a sheaf of grain
        harvested at the proper time!  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWe have studied life and found all this to be true.\n\tListen
        to my counsel, and apply it to yourself.\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: "Job\u2019s Second Speech: A Response to Eliphaz"
      content: 'Then Job spoke again:  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CIf my misery could be weighed\n\tand my troubles be put on
        the scales,  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "they would outweigh all the sands of the sea.\n\tThat is why I spoke
        impulsively.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "For the Almighty has struck me down with his arrows.\n\tTheir poison
        infects my spirit.\n\tGod\u2019s terrors are lined up against me.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Don\u2019t I have a right to complain?\n\tDon\u2019t wild donkeys
        bray when they find no grass,\n\tand oxen bellow when they have no food?  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Don\u2019t people complain about unsalted food?\n\tDoes anyone want
        the tasteless white of an egg?[COMMENT[0]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '6:6 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: the tasteless juice of the mallow plant?
    - title: 
      content: "My appetite disappears when I look at it;\n\tI gag at the thought
        of eating it!  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201COh, that I might have my request,\n\tthat God would grant my
        desire.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I wish he would crush me.\n\tI wish he would reach out his hand and
        kill me.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "At least I can take comfort in this:\n\tDespite the pain,\n\tI have
        not denied the words of the Holy One.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But I don\u2019t have the strength to endure.\n\tI have nothing to
        live for.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Do I have the strength of a stone?\n\tIs my body made of bronze?  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "No, I am utterly helpless,\n\twithout any chance of success.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201COne should be kind to a fainting friend,\n\tbut you accuse
        me without any fear of the Almighty.[COMMENT[0]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '6:14 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: friend, / or he might lose his fear of the Almighty.
    - title: 
      content: "My brothers, you have proved as unreliable as a seasonal brook\n\tthat
        overflows its banks in the spring  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'when it is swollen with ice and melting snow.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But when the hot weather arrives, the water disappears.\n\tThe brook
        vanishes in the heat.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The caravans turn aside to be refreshed,\n\tbut there is nothing
        to drink, so they die.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The caravans from Tema search for this water;\n\tthe travelers from
        Sheba hope to find it.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They count on it but are disappointed.\n\tWhen they arrive, their
        hopes are dashed.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "You, too, have given no help.\n\tYou have seen my calamity, and you
        are afraid.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But why? Have I ever asked you for a gift?\n\tHave I begged for anything
        of yours for myself?  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Have I asked you to rescue me from my enemies,\n\tor to save me from
        ruthless people?  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Teach me, and I will keep quiet.\n\tShow me what I have done wrong.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Honest words can be painful,\n\tbut what do your criticisms amount
        to?  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Do you think your words are convincing\n\twhen you disregard my cry
        of desperation?  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You would even send an orphan into slavery[COMMENT[0]]or sell a friend.  '
      comments:
      - number: '6:27 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: even gamble over an orphan.
    - title: 
      content: "Look at me!\n\tWould I lie to your face?  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Stop assuming my guilt,\n\tfor I have done no wrong.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Do you think I am lying?\n\tDon\u2019t I know the difference between
        right and wrong?"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CIs not all human life a struggle?\n\tOur lives are like that
        of a hired hand,  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "like a worker who longs for the shade,\n\tlike a servant waiting
        to be paid.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I, too, have been assigned months of futility,\n\tlong and weary
        nights of misery.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
